        "content": "<p>Suppose I have a bicategory <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span> together with a pseudofunctor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F :E \\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> restricts to a fibration on every hom-category, but it's not 'globally' a (2-)fibration.<br>\nI think the most natural name for this thing is a 'local fibration', though 'local' seems to be a bit overloaded in CT. In particular there seems to be already a thing called '<a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/local+fibration\">local fibration</a>'.<br>\nIs this thing already known? If yes, how? If no, what could be a good name?<br>\nAnother proposal: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> is 'locally fibrational'.</p>",
        "id": 223741911,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1611396191
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I've called that a \"local fibration\", e.g. Def 6.3 <a href=\"https://dlicata.wescreates.wesleyan.edu/pubs/lsr17multi/lsr17multi-ex.pdf\">here</a>.  I don't think there's much danger of confusion with the model-categorical usage.  <a href=\"http://www.irb.hr/korisnici/ibakovic/groth2fib.pdf\">Bakovic</a> talks about functors being \"locally a fibration\", while <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jpaa.2013.11.002\">Buckley</a> says that such a functor is \"locally fibred\".</p>",
        "id": 223897294,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1611581779
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks Mike! Weird, I skimmed Bakovic's paper and didn't notice he defined it.</p>",
